To draw a chessboard in LaTeX based on a given FEN notation, you can use the `skak` package. Here's a LaTeX code that includes the necessary commands and packages to achieve this:

```latex
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{skak}

\begin{document}

% Define the FEN notation
\def\FEN{rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1}

% Set up the chessboard
\newgame
\fenboard{\FEN}

% Display the chessboard
\begin{center}
\chessboard
\end{center}

\end{document}
```

Explanation:
1. We start with the standard `\documentclass` declaration, specifying the document class as `article`.

2. We include the `skak` package using `\usepackage{skak}`. This package provides commands for typesetting chess games and diagrams.

3. Inside the `document` environment, we define the FEN notation using `\def\FEN{...}`. Replace the FEN string with the actual FEN notation you want to use.

4. We set up a new chessboard using `\newgame`. This command resets the board to its initial state.

5. We use the `\fenboard` command to set the chessboard to the state specified by the FEN notation. The `\FEN` macro is passed as an argument to `\fenboard`.

6. To display the chessboard, we use the `center` environment to center the chessboard on the page. Inside the `center` environment, we use the `\chessboard` command to render the chessboard.

7. Finally, we end the `document` environment.

When you compile this LaTeX code, it will generate a document with the chessboard drawn according to the provided FEN notation.

Note: Make sure you have the `skak` package installed in your LaTeX distribution. If it's not already installed, you may need to install it using your LaTeX package manager or by downloading it from CTAN (Comprehensive TeX Archive Network).

